  "prompt": "What is the difference between earned and unearned income?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the key differences between earned and unearned income:\n\nEarned Income:\n- Money received from working a job or performing services\n- Includes wages, salaries, tips, commissions, and self-employment earnings\n- Requires active effort and personal labor to generate\n- Subject to payroll taxes like Social Security and Medicare\n- Can contribute to retirement accounts like 401(k) and IRA\n\nUnearned Income:\n- Money received without active work or labor\n- Includes interest, dividends, capital gains, rental income, alimony, inheritance\n- Passive sources of income that don't require direct personal effort\n- Often taxed differently than earned income\n- Generally not subject to payroll taxes\n- Does not qualify for retirement account contributions\n\nExamples of earned income:\n- Hourly wages\n- Annual salary\n- Freelance work\n- Consulting fees\n\nExamples of unearned income:\n- Stock dividends\n- Bank account interest\n- Investment returns\n- Rental property income\n- Social Security benefits\n- Pension payments\n\nThe main distinction is that earned income comes from active work, while unearned income comes from investments, assets, or other passive sources.",
